					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I'd personally start off with a simple audio photodiode detector, something like this:<div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<img src="./download/file.php?id=651" alt="light-detector.png" /><br />
			<span class="gensmall">light-detector.png [ 521 Bytes | Viewed 682 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br />It's an utterly stupid schematic, and can easily be railed. But it involves very minimal parts. I used a three AAs, two 2N3704s, a red LED, and my headphones. (LEDs can be used as photodiodes, hence why I've marked one, since I have tons of LEDs lying around. If you have a real photodiode, or a phototransistor, you could use it instead)<br />Better designs would use op amps and high-pass filters to make it more robust.<br />After, you could replace the speaker with a resistor and connect that to one of the NES's input pins.</div>

